Ri did not mention plans for a second Kim-Trump summit as the US leader highlighted in the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the party on this matter of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a deadlock."
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year's when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's future ability to reach the mainland with rockets was inevitable after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, commended Kim for his courage to take measures to disarm, but it said that much work still remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
