The National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
We hope that the results will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and contribute to directing future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the South and Dwarf Pistrell as well as brown borrowed and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in important places around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area view of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have decreased significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects housing and the loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose risks, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from house taxes.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in catching the prey.
They use sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats seriously.
The organisation has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out investigations, examines the housing and sometimes performs rescue operations.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threeave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says that the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here at Threeave we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veterans and a lot of beneficial habitats.
But there is much about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before carrying out maintenance in real estate, since it is possible that accidental destruction of a single dwelling could kill up to 400 females and young people, and possibly wipe out an entire population.
Flatter mice are peaceful and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or destroy their nest.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations feel."
